<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06138240 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06138240 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; The queen stands on a riser at the House podium  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  UK; WOMAN; LEADER; TRIP; LIST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The first British monarch to address Congress stood before that solemn bodyThursday and pointedly addressed the issue that has preoccupied both nations'capitals for several days: her royal headgear.;    &quot;I do hope you can see metoday from where you are,&quot; Queen Elizabeth II said in clipped tones, bringingher audience to its feet in gales of laughter.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  QUEEN'S VISIT WOWS CONGRESS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     See her they could, since the folks who prepared the lectern in the Housechamber took care not to repeat Tuesday's White House hat flap.;    At herwelcoming ceremony, the 5-foot, 4-inch queen was dubbed &quot;the talking hat&quot;because a wall of microphones obscured her face so television viewers saw onlythe brim of her purple-and-white boater.;    The queen managed to get throughWednesday in a variety of millinery without incident. Another potentialprotocol breach was avoided when lawmakers decided to scrap the traditionagainst hats in the chamber for her Thursday speech, which was delivered undera tangerine straw number.;    Members of the House and Senate and thediplomatic corps gave the queen a standing ovation as she entered, and HouseSpeaker Thomas Foley, D-Wash., an enthusiastic Anglophile, introduced thequeen and her husband to a packed chamber.;    Some House members boycottedthe speech for political reasons.;    Rep. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., said heand several colleagues did not attend &quot;in protest to the British occupation inNorthern Ireland.&quot; Rep. Gus Savage, D-Mich., urged his black colleagues tostay away because Britain recently lifted sanctions against South Africa.;   In her 15-minute speech -- the first substantive piece of business on hernine-day official visit -- the queen lauded U.S.-British cooperation in thePersian Gulf war but said more remains to be done.;    &quot;Unfortunately,experience shows that great enterprises seldom end with a tidy andsatisfactory flourish,&quot; she said.;    Referring to the Kurds who have fledIraq fearing persecution by President Saddam Hussein, the queen said theallies are &quot;doing our best to re-establish peace and civil order in theregion, and to help those members of ethnic and religious minorities whocontinue to suffer through no fault of their own.&quot;;    As dictated by Britishlaw, the queen was not expressing her own opinion, but the views of thegovernment, headed by conservative Prime Minister John Major.;    EarlierThursday, the queen stopped at the Folger Shakespeare Library to visit theworld's largest collection of Shakespeare First Folios, the 1623 firsteditions of the complete works.;    After an afternoon visit to Mount Vernon,George Washington's home along the Potomac River south of Washington, thequeen's last event in the capital was a black-tie dinner at the BritishEmbassy. She leaves for Florida today.;  The royal; itinerary; As the queen'snine-day visit continues, her schedule today includes:; (box)A visit to theNational Cathedral.; (box)Departure for Miami.; After today:; (box)Weekend:Visits to Miami and Tampa; cruising on royal yacht, Brittania.; (box)Monday:Stops in Tampa, Fla., and Austin, Texas.; (box)Tuesday: Tour of the Alamo inSan Antonio; visits to the Symphony Center and Garden Center in Dallas.;(box)Tuesday-Thursday: Visits to the Johnson Space Center and other sights inHouston.; (box)Thursday: Departure for Lexington, Ky., for weekend stay at thehorse farm of longtime Bush friend Will Farish; queen will visit some of herAmerican-stabled brood mares.; Source: Mercury News wire services  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  S